<h2 id="section-3">Section 3: Modifying the Files</h2>

<ul>
  <li>Lets add some basic structure to our HTML code.
    <ol style=1>
      <li>Remove the <strong>"Hello World" </strong>paragraph tag.</li>
      <li>Add two input fields to your <strong>index.html</strong> inside the <strong>body</strong> tag at the top: </li>
      <ul>
        <li> One for <strong>Teammate Name</strong>:
          <pre>
        &lt;label &gt; Teammate Name &lt;/label &gt;
        &lt;input type="text" id="memberName"/&gt;
          </pre>
        </li>
        <li> One for <strong>Teammate Age</strong>:
          <pre>
        &lt;label&gt; Teammate Age &lt;/label&gt;
        &lt;input type="number" id="memberAge"/&gt;
          </pre>
        </li>
        <li> A <strong>Save</strong> button
          <pre>
    &lt;div&gt; 
        &lt;button class="btn btn-default" ng-click="saveMember()"&gt;Save
            &lt;span class="glyphicon glyphicon-ok"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;
      	&lt;/button&gt; 
    &lt;/div&gt; 
       	   </pre>
        </li>
        <li>
            Your code should be like below:
            <img src="/~cs110x/static/img/lab5/index2.png" alt="image10" />
        </li>
        <li>
            The display of your website should be like below:
            <img src="/~cs110x/static/img/lab5/website1.png" alt="image10" />
        </li>
        
      </ul>
      <li>
          Next  you need to set up the basic file structure for your angular web application:
          <ol style="1">
            <li>First you need a new file called <strong>app.js</strong>
              this will contain the Angular module that you need to connect your
              JavaScript to the displayed HTML. You can create a new file by pressing
              <strong>right click</strong> on the left margin of the Brackets' page and
              selecting <strong>New File</strong>.
              <ul>
                <li>Inside the <strong>app.js</strong> add the following code:
<pre>
/*global angular*/
angular.module('ngTeam', ['ui.bootstrap']);
</pre>
                    You might think that the <strong>"/*global angular*/"</strong>comment is
                    just an ordinary comment, if you remove it and then save the file using 
                    <strong> Ctrl + s</strong> keys, you should get an error message
                    like below: <br />
                    <strong> 'angular' was used before it was defined. </strong>	
                </li>
             </ul>
            </li>
            <li>
              Next, navigate to the <strong>FirebaseApp</strong> folder and create a new 
              subfolder called <strong>ng-team</strong>. 
            </li>
            <li>
              Inside <strong>ng-team</strong> create a new file called <strong>
              teamController.js</strong> by selecting <strong>File -&gt; New</strong>
            </li>
            <li>
              Now you need to connect these new files to your index.html file.
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Inside the first <strong>body</strong> tag add the <strong>ng-app</strong>
                  and <strong>ng-controller</strong> fields:
                  <pre>
      &lt;body ng-app="ngTeam" ng-controller="teamController"&gt;
                  </pre>
                  This connects the created JavaScript files to your HTML.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>
              Now it is time for coding some Angular functionalities. Angular has built in Model View Controller (MVC). 
              <ul>
                <li>Lets build your model inside your HTML first:
                    <br />
                    You can do this by adding the Angular <strong>ng-model</strong> inside
                    your &lt;input&gt; labels. Follow the example below:
                    <pre>
&lt;input type="text" id="memberName" ng-model="teammate.name"/&gt;  
&lt;input type="number" id="memberAge" ng-model="teammate.age"/&gt;
                    </pre>
                    Now these inputs are associated with a <strong>teammate</strong> field
                    that has properties of <strong>name</strong> and <strong>age</strong>.
                    <br/ >
                    Also connect your button to the Angular ng-click property which will call
                    <strong>saveMemeber</strong> function that you will write in future:
                    <pre>
&lt;button class="btn btn-default" ng-click="saveMember()"&gt;
                    </pre>
                    <br />
                    Now add some Angular code to display the model properties to the user.
                    Below the <strong>Save</strong> button add the HTML code:
                    <pre>
       Team Member Name: {{teammate.name}} &lt;br/&gt;
       Team Member Age: {{teammate.age}}               
                    </pre>
                    The {{}} allow you to insert Angular JavaScript directly into your HTML
                    which will "data-bind" the value of this variable meaning that it will
                    change in HTML as soon as it is changed in JavaScript.
                    <br />
                    Your HTML code now should be like below:
                    <img src="/~cs110x/static/img/lab5/index3.png" alt="image11" />
                </li>
              </ul> 
            </li>
            <li>
              Now start building a controller for your model.
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Open <strong>teamController.js</strong>, then add the following code to the file:
                  <pre>
  /*global alert,angular,Firebase*/
  angular
    .module('ngTeam')
    .controller('teamController', function ($scope) {

      'use strict';
      $scope.saveMember = function() {
        alert('You have saved: ' + $scope.teammate.name);
      };
    });
                  </pre>
                  <strong>1.</strong> This code creates an anonymous function for the controller. The $scope gives access 
                  to the html because you linked both the module and controller inside 
                  the &lt;body&gt; already.<br />
                  <strong>2.</strong> You instantiate the $scope.teammate field for your model here as well. 
                  This is what you are appending your "name" and "age" field to inside the html model.<br />
                  <strong>3.</strong> Finally the $scope.saveMember is the function that is called by the user upon click. This for now will just send and alert so you can test it and make sure it works.<br />
                </li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ol>    
      </li>
      <li>
        Now it is time to make sure that your code functions correctly.
        <ul>
          <li>Go back to your live preview and hit refresh. Make sure all files are saved.
              The live preview should look like the below picture.
              <img src="/~cs110x/static/img/lab5/preview1.png" alt="image12" />
              Notice how as you type information into the form it was automatically displayed 
              in the text below? That is because of a very cool feature of Angular called two 
              way data binding. As you edit a variable the results are immediately fed back to
              the HTML. Angular uses this feature to facilitate its implementation of the 
              Model-View-Controller (MVC) architectural pattern. 
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </li>
