<h2 id="section-4">Section 4: Plugging in Firebase</h2>

<ul>
  <li>Log in to Firebase and then click on <strong>CREATE NEW PROJECT</strong>.
    <ul>
      <li>Insert <strong>CSE110project</strong> inside the <strong>Project name</strong> place holder.
          Then click <strong>CREATE PROJECT.</strong>
      </li>
      <li>It will take a few second for the fire base to create your project and then
          when it is finaly done it will automatically direct you to the Dashboard of the
          project. (If in anycase it did not take you there just simply click on your project box and it will 
          take you there).
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Add new entries to your data.
    <ul>
      <li>
        In the homepage of your project click on the <strong>Database</strong> tab on the left corner of the
        page. This will open up the <strong>Realtime Database</strong> page where it stores your data entries.
        (If your page was missing some context or was not complete based on the image below just refresh
        the page until it looks similar to the image).
        <img src="/~cs110x/static/img/lab5/SetUpF1.png" alt="SetUpF1" />

      </li>
      <li>
        Now move your cursor on the bold text starting with <strong>cse110project-</strong> and then you will see a green plus button appears on the same line, clcik on the plus button. Then fill in the <strong>Name</strong> and <strong>Value</strong> with anything and then click on <strong>ADD</strong> button.
        <img src="/~cs110x/static/img/lab5/SetUpF2.png" alt="SetUpF2" />
      </li> 
      <li>
        Fire base stores its information as name value pairs as you can see above. Underneath the hood, Firebase is built on top of NoSQL or a "non-relational" database.
        <ul>
          <li>
            You can read more about this here:
            <a href="https://www.mongodb.com/nosql-explained">nosql-explained</a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> In order to be able to add and retrieve the information from Firebase you should make the data base of this project both readable
      and writeable to the public. To do this select the <strong>RULES</strong> option on the top of the page.
      <img src="/~cs110x/static/img/lab5/RolesF1.png" alt="RolesF1" />
      Now remove "auth != null" from the two lines and write true instead like shown below and then click <strong>PUBLISH</strong>.
      <img src="/~cs110x/static/img/lab5/RolesF2.png" alt="RolesF2" />
      For more information on the permissions in Firebase go to this link:
      <a href="https://firebase.google.com/docs/database/security/quickstart">Security</a>.
      </li>
      
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>
    Create a Firebase object in controller using Firebase URL:
    <ul>
      <li>
        Copy the URL from your database and paste it into your controller.
         <img src="/~cs110x/static/img/lab5/SetUpF2.png" alt="SetUpF3" />
        Open <strong>teamController.js</strong> and before the <strong>saveMemeber</strong> function add the following line and replace
        https://fiery-inferno-4197.firebaseio.com with <strong> your own Firebase URL:</strong>
        <pre>
$scope.myData = new Firebase("https://fiery-inferno-4197.firebaseio.com");
        </pre>
      </li>
      <li> The myData variable will allow you to manipulate your Firebase database from within your code. Read about the functionalities below. Only a few of this functionalities are covered in this lab.
      <br />
      <a href = "https://www.firebase.com/docs/web/guide">Guide</a>
      <br />
      Firebase uses JSON objects to store its information if you're not familiar with JSON you can learn more about it by going to the link below.
      <br />
      <a href = "https://www.firebase.com/json">JSON</a>
  
      </li>
      <li>
        Now lets push the data to Firebase. Add the following code into your saveMember() method:
        <pre>
    $scope.myData.push($scope.teammate);
    //This is just to empty the Name and Age fields after saving
    $scope.teammate.name = "";  
    $scope.teammate.age = 0;

        </pre>
      </li>
      <li>
        Now you need to add the Firebase library:
        <ul>
          <li>
            Visit <a href="https://www.firebase.com/docs/web/quickstart.html">Quick Start</a>.
          </li>
          <li>
            Copy the CDN to your file on the line above the other scripts in <strong>index.html</strong>.
            <pre>
&lt;script src="https://cdn.firebase.com/js/client/2.4.2/firebase.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;          
            </pre>
          </li>

        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>
        Now lets add a person to the data basee. Again click on the lightning bolt to open the browser and fill in the fields with some inputs and then click <strong>Submit</strong>.
      </li>
      <li>After submition go back to your Firebase/Database page and you should see that the new object is added to your Data base. If you expand the objec by clicking on it, it should show you the name and the age you inserted.
      <img src="/~cs110x/static/img/lab5/SetUpF4.png" alt="SetUpF4"/>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>
    Let's now add some structure to this databae so that it is more readable.
    <ul>
      <li>
        The <strong>push</strong> function you used above creates a unique key in the database and inserts your data below that. This is the "Kc60..." number above your data.
      </li>
      <li>
        If you would like yo choose the key associated with your data you can use the <strong>set</strong> method.
      </li>
      <li>
        To begin lets add a field to our html file in place of our first label "Teammate Name", so remove the label "Teammate Name" with the corresponding input fields and add the code below.
        <pre>
  &lt;label&gt;Teammate First Name&lt;/label&gt;
  &lt;input type="text" id="memberName" ng-model="teammate.name"&gt;&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;label&gt;Teammate FullName&lt;/label&gt;
  &lt;input type="text" id="memberFullName" ng-model="teammate.full_name"&gt;&lt;br&gt;

        </pre>
        <ul>
          <li>The first filed will be the first name and key for your database entry.</li>
          <li>The second field will store the team members full name</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>
        Next lets change how you are displaying the real-time data entry using an Angular filter:
        <ul>
          <li>Remove the Team Member Name and Age fields. Replace the tags inside of index.html with the line below:
            <pre>
        &lt;pre&gt;{{teammate | json}}&lt;/pre&gt;
            </pre>

          </li>


          <li>
            The result should be like the image below:
            <img src="/~cs110x/static/img/lab5/ResultF1.png" alt="ResultF1"/>
            In case you did something wrong please look at the images below and make sure that everything looks the same:<br />
            <strong>index.html:</strong>
            <img src="/~cs110x/static/img/lab5/index.png" alt="SetUpF4"/><br />
            <strong>teamController.js</strong>
            <img src="/~cs110x/static/img/lab5/teamController.png" alt="SetUpF4"/>
          </li>
        </ul>

      </li>
      <li>
        Next update your teamController file, add the following code after the line "$scope.myData = new Firebase...".
        <pre>
        $scope.teammate = {};
        </pre>
        This allows you to create a name vlaue pairs, instead of an array. This is how JSON objects are formatted.
      </li>
      <li>
        Next replace the code inside the saveMemebr method with:
        <pre> 
    var teammateRef, entryKey;
    /*Creates a ref to the teammates table of the database*/
    teammateRef = $scope.myData.child("teammates");
    /*Use this for your key to enter data*/
    entryKey = $scope.teammate.name;
    teammateRef.child(entryKey).set($scope.teammate);
    /*Will erase the fields on the screen containing the name and age*/
    $scope.teammate.name = "";
    $scope.teammate.full_name = "";
    $scope.teammate.age = 0;
        </pre>
      </li>
      <li>
        Now try again adding a new entry to the data base and check your Firebase to make sure that it is added.
        <img src="/~cs110x/static/img/lab5/TeammateAdded.png" alt="TeammateAdded" />
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li id="retrievedata">
    Retrieve data from data base:
    <ul>
      <li>How do you pull data back from data base to the webpage?

      </li>
      <li>Start by creating new fields in the controller after "$scope.teammate" line, (for the second field use your own Firebase URL with the /teammates at the end):
        <pre>
  $scope.teammatesData = {};
  $scope.myTeammateData = new Firebase("https://cse110project-c30f3.firebaseio.com/teammates");
        </pre>
        
      </li>
      <li>
      Now add a new parameter to the controller declaration at the top call $timeout:<br/>
        <pre>
  .controller('teamController', function ($scope, $timeout) {
        </pre>
      </li>
      <li>
        Next add a new function to the $scope variable: <br />
        <pre>
  $scope.myTeammateData.on('value', function (dataSnapshot) {
      $timeout(function () {
          $scope.teammatesData = dataSnapshot.val();
      });
  });
        </pre>
        <ul>
          <li>
            This is an anonymous function called by the <storng>myTeammateData.on()</storng> method which is a listener that detects updates to the database its attached too. In this case it detects the updates to your apps database specifically the "teammates" table.
          </li>
          <li>
            Every time the table is altered this listener function is triggered and pulls all the information from your database and places it in the dataSnapshot parameter.
            <br /> For more info on <strong>.on</strong> go to <a href="https://www.firebase.com/docs/web/api/query/on.html">This Link</a>.
          </li>
          <li>
            Next you wrap your <strong>$scope.teammatesData</strong> update in the <strong>$timeout</strong> function. This loads your database when your page is initially loaded. Without it the information would only display when a change is detected.
            <br /> For more info on <strong>$timeout</strong> go to <a href="https://www.firebase.com/docs/web/libraries/angular/guide/beyond-angularfire.html">time-out link</a>
          </li>

        </ul>
        
      </li>

      
    </ul>
  </li> <!--retrieve data-->
  <li>Now use Angular to display a table of your database information:
    <ul>
      <li>In <strong>index.html</strong> add the following code below the last &lt;/div&gt;.
      <pre>
  &lt;div&gt;
    &lt;table class="table table-bordered"&gt;
      &lt;thead&gt;
        &lt;th&gt;Member Name&lt;/th&gt;
        &lt;th&gt;Member Full Name&lt;/th&gt;
        &lt;th&gt;Age&lt;/th&gt;
      &lt;/thead&gt;
      &lt;tbody ng-repeat="teamMember in teammatesData"&gt;
        {{teamMember.name}}
        &lt;tr&gt;
          &lt;td&gt;{{teamMember.name}}&lt;/td&gt;
          &lt;td&gt;{{teamMember.full_name}}&lt;/td&gt;
          &lt;td&gt;{{teamMember.age}}&lt;/td&gt;
        &lt;/tr&gt;
      &lt;/tbody&gt;
    &lt;/table&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
      </pre>
        
      </li>
      <li>
        Pay close attention to the line that reads <strong>ng-repeat="teamMember in teammatesData"</strong>. This it an angular for each loop. It takes your <strong>teammatesData</strong> you just updated in the controller method and loops over it. Everything between the <strong>tbody</strong> tags is part of this loop. Thus you are able to dynamically update a table with whatever data we pull down.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li><!--display table-->
  <li>
    Now test it and make sure that everything works perfectly as show in the image below.
    <img src="/~cs110x/static/img/lab5/FinalF1.png" alt="FinalF1"/></>
  </li>
   <h2>Completion Checkoff:</h2>
        Complete all the tasks above in order and be able to store and laod information from Firebase data base to receive full credit. Click on <strong>lightning bolt</strong> button and present the page shown in the image above to a tutor. When you complete add a ticket to the Autograder queue with one tag for the priority of your ticket and another with lab completion check tag so a member of the staff will help you. However bear in mind that you will only get checkoff
        prioirty during your own lab reservation time. During any other CSE 110 lab hour your checkoff request will
        be considered only if there are staff members who are not helping students from that lab hour. 
</ul>

  <!--
