<h2 id="section-6-downloading-and-setting-up-your-application">Section 6: Downloading and Setting up your application</h2>

<ul>
  <li>Create a new folder by typing:
    <ul>
      <li><code>mkdir parseoauth2tutorial</code></li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Go into this new directory and clone the Parse tutorial github
    <ul>
      <li><code>git clone https://github.com/ParsePlatform/CloudCodeOAuthGitHubTutorial</code></li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Go to the new directory:
    <ul>
      <li>~/parseoauth2tutorial/CloudCodeOAuthGitHubTutorial/cloud<br />
<img src="/~cs110x/static/img/lab5/image8.png" alt="image8" /></li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Next you will need to create a Cloud Code Environment for your Parse App. In the ~/‚Ä¶/CloudCodeOAuthGitHubTutorial folder type the below command.
    <ul>
      <li><code>parse new</code></li>
      <li>Then type your email and password associated with your Parse user account. It should then print out the application you have created with Parse.<br />
<img src="/~cs110x/static/img/lab5/image9.png" alt="image9" /><br />
<img src="/~cs110x/static/img/lab5/image10.png" alt="image10" /></li>
      <li>Select your App</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Now You have a <strong>parse</strong> folder that contains <strong>cloud config</strong> and <strong>public</strong> directories. These are used to interface with Parse and display a website at the address you specified in parse.
    <ul>
      <li>To push your website to Parse, navigate into the Parse folder you just created and type: <code>parse deploy</code><br />
<img src="/~cs110x/static/img/lab5/image11.png" alt="image11" /></li>
      <li>Now visit the url you created on your parse hosting page
        <ul>
          <li>‚Äúmy-site.parseapp.com‚Äù</li>
          <li>You should see the following displayed.<br />
<img src="/~cs110x/static/img/lab5/image12.png" alt="image12" /></li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Now you will move the entire <strong>parse</strong> folder into the directory above.
    <ul>
      <li><code>mv parse ..</code></li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Change directory to <strong>parse</strong> and copy <strong>cloud</strong> into <strong>parse</strong>.
    <ul>
      <li><code>cd parse</code></li>
      <li><code>cp -r ../cloud .</code></li>
      <li>This will replace the default cloud directory with the one downloaded from GitHub</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>When a <code>parse deploy</code> is executed, the cloud directory is what pushed to Parse. You can see these modifications by going to your app on Parse. Navigate to Parse Core and click on the Cloud Code section on the right. All of the files in your cloud directory should appear here.</li>
</ul>

<hr />

<h2 id="section-7-next-we-will-edit-our-downloaded-files-so-that-they-are-configured-to-communicate-with-our-application">Section 7: Next we will edit our downloaded files so that they are configured to communicate with our application</h2>

<ul>
  <li>Open <strong>main.js</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>Edit the githubClientID and githubClientSecret variables with your ID and Secret key from the GitHub page where you registered your application<br />
